<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-204-378  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 204 378.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  March 5 1990 v7 n9 p141(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Slump in earnings for Microamerica prompts revision of Softselmerger. (Softsel Computer Products Inc, Microamerica Inc)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   MicroAmerica Inc. (acquisitions and mergers)Softsel Computer Products Inc. (acquisitions and mergers).andO;Ticker:    SOFS.andO;Topic:     AcquisitionMergerDistributorsComputer industryProfitFinancial Stability.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Microamerica Inc.'s lower-than-expected earnings for the fourth quarter haveled Softsel Computer Products Inc. and Microamerica to cut a new deal fortheir proposed merger.andM;The merger, announced in November, brings together two of the largestdistributors of computer products, creating a $1 billion company.andM;Under the new merger terms, agreed upon two weeks ago, every Microamericashareholder will receive 0.9 shares of Softsel stock for each Microamericashare he or she owns.andP;  In addition, if the price of Softsel's stock is lessthan $7.82 at the time of the merger -- which is scheduled to be finalized atthe shareholders' meeting taking place March 28 -- then Microamericashareholders will also receive a cash payment, determined by a formula, foreach share.andM;&quot;The deal was restated because Microamerica's results were lower thanexpected,&quot; said Jim Brill, chief financial officer of Softsel in El Segundo,Calif.andM;Although Microamerica's sales for the fourth quarter ended Dec.andP;  31 increased28 percent to $143 million, compared with $111 million for the same period ayear ago, net income dropped.andP;  Net income broke even at $76,000, or zerocents per share -- down from $2.36 million, or 18 cents per share, for lastyear's fourth quarter.andM;The poor financial results stemmed from problems and costs associated withstarting up Microamerica's new main distribution center in Lee Summit, Mo.,andO;said Robert Muccini, chief financial officer of the company, which isheadquartered in Marlboro, Mass.andP;  Although the new center began operating inJuly, Muccini claimed that computer and mechanical problems at the centeraffected the fourth-quarter results.andM;Muccini said the inventory buildup of the fourth quarter and the interestcosts associated with that inventory may also have a negative effect onMicroamerica's upcoming first-quarter results.andM;In addition, net income for the year dropped dramatically, down to $5.31million, or 39 cents per share, compared with $8.31 million, or 62 cents pershare, for 1988.andM;In 1989, Microamerica reported net sales of $526 million, up from $405million in 1988.andO;</TEXT></DOC>